## 3. The n=6 outlier — routing-composition signature

### 3.1 Pre-registration

Five routings of f^(1/6), all mathematically identical:

- R1: `f ** (1/6)` (Python `**`)
- R2: `(f**(1/3))**(1/2)` (sqrt of cbrt)
- R3: `(f**(1/2))**(1/3)` (cbrt of sqrt)
- R4: `math.exp(math.log(f)/6)` (explicit exp/log)
- R5: `float(np.power(f, 1/6))` (numpy.power)

Same sweep, same eta, agnostic mode.

### 3.2 Per-point g(f) identity matrix

Max absolute difference in g(f) across the 12-point sweep:

| Pair | max \|Δ\| |
|---|---|
| R1 ≡ R3 ≡ R5 (Python `**`, cbrt(sqrt), numpy.power) | **0** (bit-identical) |
| R2 (sqrt(cbrt)) vs the R1≡R3≡R5 cluster | 1 ULP |
| R4 (exp(log/6)) vs all others | ~4 ULPs |

Python's `**(1/6)` is empirically bit-identical to `(f^(1/2))^(1/3)` and to `numpy.power(f, 1/6)` at every sweep point. The libm `pow(x, 1/6)` path that Python and numpy share happens to coincide with the `cbrt(sqrt(f))` composite at our precision. The `sqrt(cbrt(f))` composite differs (operand order matters at the ULP level). The explicit `exp(log/6)` decomposition is the most divergent of the five.

### 3.3 V4-chain bias per routing

| Routing | observed_α | bias | std_err | \|bias/σ\| | structural signature |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| R1 Python `**(1/6)` | 0.16666666661352725 | −5.31e-11 | 1.45e-11 | 3.67 | systematic, tight |
| R2 sqrt(cbrt(f)) | 0.16666666661879160 | −4.79e-11 | 2.63e-11 | 1.82 | systematic, medium scatter |
| R3 cbrt(sqrt(f)) | 0.16666666663384289 | −3.28e-11 | 1.66e-11 | 1.98 | systematic, medium scatter |
| R4 exp(log(f)/6) | 0.16666666665295450 | −1.37e-11 | 7.56e-11 | 0.18 | high scatter, low bias |
| R5 numpy.power | **0.16666666661352725** | **−5.31e-11** | **1.45e-11** | **3.67** | bit-identical to R1 through V4 chain |

R1 and R5 produce identical observed_α to all 17 displayed digits, identical window_span (2.88e-11), and identical std_err (1.45e-11). The bit-identity of g(f) propagates through finite-difference, log-log fit, and OLS slope to the V4-chain output.

R3 has bit-identical g(f) to R1 but a meaningfully different observed_α (−3.28e-11 vs −5.31e-11, a 2e-11 gap). The g(f) table covers only the sweep points; the divergence must live in g(f+δf) — i.e., the operand-perturbed evaluation. A 1-ULP difference at perturbed-operand points propagates through finite-difference + OLS to a ~2e-11 swing in α.

### 3.4 Substrate-to-α amplification factor

For R1 vs R3 (bit-identical at f, presumed 1-ULP off at some f+δf):

- ULP at g(f), f=1e-9, α=1/6: g ≈ 0.0316, ULP ≈ 5.6e-18.
- Difference at g(f+δf): ~1 ULP ≈ 5.6e-18.
- Resulting α difference: 2e-11.
- **Amplification factor ≈ 10⁶.**

This is the substrate-to-α-reading amplification for the standard sweep configuration. Single-ULP routing-composition differences in the operand-perturbed evaluation become ~10⁻¹¹ in the recovered α.

### 3.5 Refined IEEE-mandate taxonomy

The earlier framing of the taxonomy was binary:
- **Mandated** (sqrt, +/-, ×, /, FMA, remainder, conversions): bit-exact identity across implementations
- **Implementation-free** (cbrt, pow, exp, log, transcendentals): free to vary

Today's data refines this:

- **Bit-identity of different routings is empirically possible in the implementation-free class** when implementations dispatch through the same libm (R1 ≡ R5 for `**(1/6)`).
- **The variation in the implementation-free class is *compositional*, not merely *implementational***: different mathematical decompositions of the same operation (R2 vs R3 vs R4) reliably produce different per-point ULP signatures even when all dispatch through libm-class primitives.
- For substrate-as-probe purposes, **routing-diversity is most informative when it varies the composition, not the call site**.

